result.execSummary:
The defendant Tauheed J Graves was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Based upon the defendant's compliance with the conditions of probation, the Court ordered that time in the House of Correction, which was ordered as a condition of probation but stayed to today's date, be stayed for use at the agent's discretion in the future.
Count three.
Counts one and two.

Defendant Tauheed J Graves in court with attorney Matthew Adrian Lamke.  Elizabeth Longo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
cab
The parties are in court for sentencing.  Statements as to sentencing by the state and defense.
As to count 3:
  The Court ordered the Defendant to serve 121 days in the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence with credit for 121 days time served.  
As to counts 1 and 2:
.  Court sentenced the defendant to serve 90 days in the House of Correction as to count 1 and 9 months in the House of Correction as to count 2, consecutive, with credit for -0- days served.  Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 2 years, concurrent,  with the following conditions:
- Serve 60 days in the House of Correction; STAYED pending review.
- Complete batterer's intervention program.
- Complete a course in anger management.
- Attend parenting classes.
- Mental health evaluation; take all prescribed medications.
- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety; random urine screens.
- Attend treatment and/or counseling as determined.  The agent is to determine if the defendant is to participate in any or all of the above programs.
- The defendant is to have no direct or violent contact with victim and only non-direct contact when arranging for time with the child.
- No contact with firearms.
- Pay all other costs and surcharges; civil judgment if not paid.  The court found that the defendant is unable to pay the DV surcharge.
- Pay supervision fees.
